args: Does it have something to do with your\nnot being accompanied by Sir Leif?
Oh, who cares where that blockhead is?
Would you like to talk about it?
I'm afraid it is rather a personal matter,\nand not something I should be discussing\nwith guests from abroad.
But surely we are friends now?
And as your friend, I seek only to lend\nyou an ear and some comfort.
Well, I suppose there IS something\nI would like to get off my chest...
You see, I was once engaged.
But my fiancé tried to sell us out to\nGrams...and I was the one who brought\nhim to justice.
That experience taught me how hard it is\nto find someone you can share even your\ndeepest ambitions with.

And now I've experienced something
similar yet again. One thing people never
understand about royalty is how so very
LONELY it can be.
You have to be constantly on your guard\nto ensure you aren't being used.
I know just how you feel.
Being royalty doesn't mean you always\nget what you want—far from it, in fact.
We are both princesses, and I believe we\nunderstand each other better than anyone\nelse possibly can.
As this is the start of a lifelong friendship,\nperhaps we should consult with—and \nconfide in—each other?
It as you say. We are frien—
Where did that explosion come from?!
This is clearly the work of a Grams\nassassin who seeks to thwart our alliance!
Evacuate the other guests at once.
Lead the search for the assassin while I\nescort Princess Yelda to safety.
Will you be all right on your own?
Yes—in fact, that will be more expedient.\nI will await your good news.
It is a manacaster research facility\nreconstructed from ancient ruins.
Connected directly to the palace?\nHeavens, what a thing.
Surprising, isn't it? Only a few know of\nthis evacuation route, so hopefully the\nassassin is not among them.
Is it wise for us to travel together like this\nwithout guard or escort?
Normally it wouldn't be,\nbut this is a unique situation.
My palace's defenses are second to none,\nyet someone breached your very room.
This has the stink of treachery about it.
Yes, if the culprit were one of my own\nguards or servants...
It would have been a simple matter for\nthem to plant something in your room.
And if that were the case, they might have\nbeen hoping for us to evacuate along with\nall of the others.
They could finish the job as they liked\nbefore disappearing into a sea of people.
As such, I'm sure you see the wisdom in\nstaying put until we hear from Cat Sìth.
I'm quite impressed, Chelle.\nYou really thought this through.
...But I'm afraid I did as well.
It would be best if you didn't make any\nsudden movements, Your Highness.
I'm not terribly used to casters yet,\nand I'd hate for this to go off by accident.
I'm sorry to say that I lied to you.
I said we hadn't yet developed any \noperable manacasters in Fadden...
But in truth, we succeeded in restoring\none of the weapons we excavated.
Oh? You simply MUST tell me\nhow you managed such a feat.
Using intelligence our spies extracted\nfrom Chanzelia, of course.
But restoring just this one took an\nimmense amount of time. We're nowhere\nnear mass production.
Hence the inclusion of the joint\ndevelopment pact in our treaty.
A treaty scheduled to be ratified tomorrow,\nmight I add. So why would you resort to\nthis manner of treachery now?
We have received a more favorable offer...
One from the Holy City of Grams.
And here I thought the two of you\ndidn't get along.

In exchange for your assassination and
all of the stolen manacaster technology,
they have agreed to cede a food-producing
region of their territory to us.
So the explosion was just another\npart of your trap.
You made it look like you were the target\nso you might isolate me instead...
Yes...to everyone else, it would appear\nthat the host nation's princess bravely gave\nher life to protect her guest.
Still, aren't you forgetting something?\nThat caster will be of little use if I\ndecide to shapeshift.
You would never take an action that\nmight plunge your land into war.
If I were to be killed by a dragon,\nall suspicion would fall on you.
And if I am slain by a caster, it will be\neasy to lay blame at the feet of one from\nChanzelia who opposes the alliance.
Exactly! For how could I slay you when\nwe possess no such weaponry?!
Speaking of which, I will be able to pilfer\nsome fine technology from this facility.\nYou were a trusting fool to lead me here.
All that's left is to pull this trigger\nand save my country from famine!
Is that truly what this is about?
Fadden was presented with two choices:\nunite with Alberia or unite with Grams.
Both choices have merit on the surface,\nbut do you trust Grams to follow through?\nTRULY trust them, I mean?

After all, this is the very country that
meddles endlessly in your affairs—the
very country whose yoke you seek to
cast off your collective necks.
And yet you take their offer over mine.
Ah, but it is a shame how quickly everyone\nlooks for the easy way out.
In fact, Chanzelia once had a weak-minded\nruler who sought the easy path.
I would thank you to keep his name\nout of your unworthy mouth.
It is your fault he died! Yours!
Elua loved peace above all,\nand his death is on YOUR head!
